#PostcardsfromLadakh

Leh Palace (Lachen Palkar Palace) & Street View 
Circa 1902 

Leh Palace, also known as Lachen Palkar Palace, is a former royal palace overlooking the city of Leh in Ladakh, India. It was constructed circa 1600 AD by Sengge Namgyal. The palace was abandoned when Dogra forces took control of Ladakh in the mid-19th century and forced the royal family to move to Stok Palace.

The palace is being restored by the Archaeological Survey of India.

latestPosts.caption:
#PostcardsfromLadakh

Traditional Ladakhi attire is more than clothing - It’s an embodiment of culture, climate, and continuity.

Elements of the Ensemble:
• Goncha – The long woollen robe, worn by both men and women
• Sulma – A pleated gown worn by women
• Tipi – Woollen hat, often adorned with embellishments
• Lokpa – A heavy cloak offering warmth and elegance
• Perak – A turquoise-studded headdress symbolising lineage and status
• Jewellery – Neckpieces, amulets, and earrings carrying spiritual and social meaning

Each element reflects the region’s resilience and reverence for tradition - stitched, pleated, and set in stone over generations.

Image source : @pinterest

#PostcardsfromLadakh

Often known as the ‘moonland’ of Leh-Ladakh, the quaint village of Lamayuru is famous its ‘lunar’ landscape, due to its unusual geographical formations. Perched amidst its mountainous landscape are the red and white buildings of the monastery village, consisting of monks cells and farmhouses.

It is said that a scholar named Mahasiddhacharya Naropa meditated in a cave there and caused a lake to drain, revealing a site where he then laid the foundation stone of the Lamayuru monastery.  And because the water receded, the place started to get moonlike craters.

Something exciting is brewing with our Postcards of Ladakh series, stay tuned…

latestPosts.caption:
#PeopleOfHOT

@umahjacob - Director of External Relations & Outreach at India Art Fair, is instrumental in expanding its global reach and leading the Young Collectors’ Programme.

As India Art Fair continues to grow, Umah Jacob remains committed to expanding the reach of South Asian artists and fostering the next generation of collectors. If you don’t know where to start, Jacob says - just jump in. “Immerse yourself in the community. The more you see, the more you learn. And the more you learn, the more exciting your journey will be.”

Previously, she has been associated with the Modern and Contemporary South Asian departments at auction houses in India and the UK. She has worked at Bonhams and Christie’s in London and was the former Sales Coordinator for Christie’s in Mumbai, as part of the team that worked to establish their first auctions in India. Umah earned a Bachelor’s degree from St. Xavier’s College, University of Mumbai, before going on to read her MA in History of Art and Archaeology at the School of Oriental and African Studies (SOAS), University of London.

She is seen here in our Inaayat Necklace, Mirror Fort Stud Earrings & Beaded Bangle. Shop her look from our People Of HOT section on the website.
